{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529886"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14472"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14472"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.01,0.11,0.73,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55811"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7167"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14472"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41356"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2302"},{"type":"tags","id":"2422"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"7953"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37118"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55811"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of redness and itching of his penis. He denies any pain on urination or penile discharge. His last sexual partner was six months ago and he has no history of sexually transmitted infections. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, diagnosed two years ago though he is not currently on any medication. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Genital examination reveals erythema and oedema of the glans penis and foreskin, with some white, cheese-like material beneath the foreskin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lichen sclerosus","Psoriasis","Chlamydia","Balanitis","Genital herpes"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebalanitis\u003C/strong\u003E, which refers to inflammation of the glans penis, often accompanied by inflammation of the foreskin (balanoposthitis). The patient\u0027s symptoms of redness and itching of the penis, along with the presence of white, cheese-like material beneath the foreskin, are classic signs of fungal balanitis. The patient\u0027s history of diabetes is also significant, as poorly controlled blood sugar can increase the risk of balanitis due to increased susceptibility to fungal infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenital herpes\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with itching, but painful vesicles or ulcers are also commonly present. Additionally, genital herpes would not explain the white, cheese-like material beneath the foreskin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChlamydia\u003C/strong\u003E is a sexually transmitted infection (STI) that often causes urethritis in men, leading to symptoms such as penile discharge and dysuria. The usual incubation period for chlamydia is 1-3 weeks, which does not align with the patient\u0027s sexual history. Whilst there may not always be a typical history of a recent new sexual partner, this patient does not describe symptoms of urethritis but rather more superficial irritation of the glans penis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen sclerosus\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic inflammatory condition that can affect the genitals. It typically causes white, patchy areas on the skin that may become thin and wrinkled. The acute presentation and lack of characteristic skin changes make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E can affect the genital area, but it usually presents with well-demarcated, scaly, red plaques. While it\u0027s possible for psoriasis to occur on the penis, the presentation described is more consistent with balanitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of balanitis in this case would involve improved hygiene practices, topical antifungal treatment, and review of his diabetes control. A swab for microscopy, culture and sensitivity of the material seen under the foreskin could confirm this diagnosis but should not delay treatment. Additionally, if he has not had a recent STI screen then this could be offered as part of routine care. If symptoms persist or recur, further investigation may be necessary to rule out other causes or complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Balanitis is inflammation of the glans penis, often accompanied by inflammation of the foreskin (balanoposthitis).","Poor hygiene, diabetes, and skin conditions like psoriasis are common causes of balanitis in non-sexually active men.","Symptoms of balanitis include redness, swelling, itching, and discharge from the penis."],"references":["Edwards SK, Bunker CB, Ziller F, van der Meijden WI. 2013 European guideline for the management of balanoposthitis. Int J STD AIDS. 2014 Aug;25(9):615-26. doi: 10.1177/0956462414533099. Epub 2014 May 14. PMID: 24828553. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24828553/","Bunker CB. Management of penile dermatoses. Expert Review of Dermatology [Internet]. 2006 Apr;1(2):241\u201361. Available at: https://go.gale.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CA222988908\u0026sid=googleScholar\u0026v=2.1\u0026it=r\u0026linkaccess=abs\u0026issn=17469872\u0026p=AONE\u0026sw=w\u0026userGroupName=anon%7Efeaaac54\u0026aty=open-web-entry"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41356"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14472"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41356"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T09:47:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T09:48:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7167"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55811"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"c